//add repositories to latest Red hat backed distros 
//filetype = .repo (extension) 
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=<URL> 


//QEMU INSTALLATION
//Install all virtualization related software on dnf-distro 
//@virtualization: This installs QEMU, KVM, virt-manager (GUI), and related tools.
                 * qemu-kvm 
                 * virt-install/virtinst 
                 * virt-manager 
                 * libvirt 
                 * bridge-utils
                 * libvirt-client 
//libvirtd: libvirt daemon manages virtualization.
//virtqemud: alternative to libvert 
virtstoraged: used to manager volume pools 
//usermod -aG libvirt $(whoami): Add current user to libvirt group so root previlliges are not required 
//systemctl enable --now libvirtd: Starts libvirt service now and enable on boot. 

sudo dnf install @virtualization 
sudo systemctl enable --now libvertd X | sudo systemctl enable --now libvirtd.socket X | sudo systemctl enable --now virtqemud.socket 
sudo systemctl start virtstoraged.socket 
sudo usermod -aG libvirt $(whoami) 

TLDR; Order of Layers of Virtualization in Linux (this particular setup) 

1. The kernel (KVM Modules) 
2. Qemu (don't emulate, use virtual hardware by KVM) 
3. libvirt (API to talk to Qemu) 
4. Tools to use libvirt (virsh, libvirt-clients) 
5. virt-manager for GUI tools 

Note: Higher the layer number, the closer it is to the user. 